Update: I ended up making the ExcelJS bridge I wanted for this exact backend path: https://www.npmjs.com/package/exceljs-formula-recalc

It still does **not** turn ExcelJS into a formula engine. It serializes the workbook, runs Bilig's XLSX import/recalc/export path, then loads the recalculated bytes back into the same ExcelJS workbook and patches requested readback cells.

Minimal shape:

```ts
import ExcelJS from "exceljs";
import { recalculateExceljsWorkbook } from "exceljs-formula-recalc";

const workbook = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
await workbook.xlsx.readFile("input.xlsx");

const result = await recalculateExceljsWorkbook(workbook, {
  edits: [{ target: "Sheet1!A1", value: 9 }],
  reads: ["Sheet1!C1"],
});

console.log(result.reads["Sheet1!C1"]); // { tag: 1, value: 12 }
console.log(workbook.getWorksheet("Sheet1").getCell("C1").value);
// { formula: "A1+B1", result: 12 }

await workbook.xlsx.writeFile("recalculated.xlsx");
```

For shared-formula/XLSX-fidelity cases, I would still test the source workbook against Excel or LibreOffice. This is aimed at the common service path: ExcelJS for file I/O, deterministic Node-side formula readback after changing inputs.

Disclosure: I maintain Bilig.
